Hi! Those taking h2 fmath  how do y'all study for linear algebra? (span  LI  LC  generates  null  range  etc)And...do you actually need to state down every single definition during the proving or just state the "workings"?

Linear algebra has a lot of terminology  so u would want to make sure u understand what they mean  and how they relate to one another  and how the abstract stuff like the terms u mentioned relate to the row operations stuff in particular
You don't need to define any of the terms used  because they're all very standard and well understood

Exam wise  they'll be asking to prove the relations only right? Or there would be more to it?(Ps. I'm taking as a private candidate  so don't have any background knowledge of how exam are tested for this subject)
What u need to do in proving  eg proving that E is a subspace of X  is u need to write down the hypotheses (such as 'let x and y be in E' or 'let Î» be a real number')  then show the final statement
FM exams are very creative so honestly anything can happen  but if ur knowledge of how these concepts are related is solid  u should be able to tackle it
And of course if u haven't  watch 3B1B's video series on linear algebra
These videos are not really like a full guide to linear algebra  but more of how you should think about linear transformations and matrices and stuff
Okay  essentially  I need to understand and know the axioms required to be met for individual segment  and then to see how the different segments link up. Is that right?
About the axioms  youâ€™ll basically only see them when proving that something is a subspace  so just the 2 requirements of closed under addition and closed under scalar multiplication
But yeah u should understand each term  as in u should know what objects a term can be used on  and how the property described relates to other properties
Hmmm don't need the ones to prove whether it's a LC/ basis or whatever?
Those donâ€™t involve the axioms of linear spaces
But u need to know what those terms mean in order to prove them of course
Ah okay. This chapter making me quite confused. I'll go read up my notes again
Yeah just organise ur thinking first
Then everything will match up nicely

Like equation of circlesâ€¦ questions on reflection of circle  finding centre of circle from tangent at one point and normal at another point (all normals pass through centre of circle) 2 points with same x-coordinate  hence forming vertical chord. Make use of â€œperpendicular bisector of chord passes through centre of circleâ€ to find midpoint coordinates  and find coordinates of Centreâ€¦.

For binomial theorem Finding term independent of x. Use formula for (r+1)th termâ€¦ equate x term to x^0 term  find r. Sub r into the expressionFor eg  find x^4 term. (1-x)^2(2 + 3x)^6 for egâ€¦ expand the left one  and expand the right to get the terms that will pair with those on the left to find x^4 terms. Add up the coefficients for the answerâ€¦

Look through diff q types. How to solveA-math q are crafted in parts to help you solve subsequent parts. For example  in q on area under curve  they would ask you to find coordinates of points of intersections firstFor trigo R-formula questions  they would start with â€œshowâ€ question  then express using R-formula  then find max valueâ€¦
Trigo proving qâ€¦ use diff techniquesâ€¦ if canâ€™t prove  go on to solve the trigo equation based on the result to show or prove
A-math q guides you. They provide instructions for you to guide you through. Such instructions will be lacking in jc math
Questions like show that the function is increasing or decreasingâ€¦ look out for squared termsâ€¦ because squared term is always positive
